MAPPING: enrollment / biometric registration / face registry = domain
"persons" (NOT entries/signatures); enrolling = set, deleting the
enrollment = delete. The IMPLICIT form without the word "enroll" also
counts: presenting a FACE/PERSON to register («this is a guest's face»,
photo + «register them») = {set, persons}, NOT {classify, images}.
SEMANTIC PRINCIPLE (universal, for ALL objects):
- A verb that CREATES/SETS/WRITES/DELETES an entity (mutating) → the
  operational verb (create/set/write/delete/move/send/share): «book an
  appointment» = create events, «send the mail» = send messages, «share
  the sheet with Y» = share files.
- A verb that ASKS/PROPOSES/SUGGESTS/SHOWS (inquiry, read-only) → read:
  «propose 3 times» = read events, «show me X's files» = read files.
  The textual synthesis happens in the planner's final_answer.
- A sentence mixing both senses («if there is room, book it») → the
  MUTATING verb wins; the preliminary check is planned by the planner.
NOTE: `proposals` = INTERNAL proposals of the Metnos synth system, never
a user-facing intent: "appointment/meeting" is NEVER proposals.
SINGLE vs CONTAINER RULE:
the object is the CONTAINER (dirs, ...) when the action treats the
container as a unit (aggregate size, structure, top containers, creating
or deleting it); it is the ELEMENT (files, messages, ...) when the action
works on the individual items (reading, criterion, hash, counting THE
elements).
"find the .py files" → files (criterion on the singles).
"find the biggest directories" → dirs (on the containers).
"count the files in a folder" → find/files (you count the ELEMENTS; NOT get, NOT dirs).
"total size of the path" → dirs (aggregate on the container).

COMPOUND (MULTIPLE ACTIONS IN SEQUENCE):
If the request contains MULTIPLE actions in sequence ("do X then Y",
"find ... and write ..."), reply with a JSON ARRAY of {verb,object}
objects, ONE per action, IN EXECUTION ORDER. Each clause carries ITS own
real object, NEVER a single global object repeated. Single action → a
single JSON object, not an array.
METHOD (ALWAYS apply on long queries): FIRST segment the sentence at the
connectives (comma, "and", "then") and COUNT the verbs/imperatives; THEN
emit EXACTLY one JSON object per segment, none fewer. Every imperative is
an action: "send me/share" = send/share (NOT render); "attach/add photo
X" = an action on images (find/get); "save to the store" and "create the
sheet" are TWO distinct actions. Do not merge two imperatives into one,
do not drop the last one.
Compound examples:
"find the processes using the most memory and write a report" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"processes"},{"verb":"write","object":"files"}]
"read the closed issues and put them in a spreadsheet" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"issues"},{"verb":"create","object":"files"}]
"download the invoices from the site and mail them to me" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"urls"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]
"find the 2020 photos, compress them and send them to me" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"files"},{"verb":"compress","object":"files"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]
LONG examples (5-6 actions, mixed domains — count the segments, one per imperative):
"download the report from https://s.it/r.pdf, save it to /tmp, email it to the team, set a reminder tomorrow and attach the chart chart.png" →
  [{"verb":"read","object":"urls"},{"verb":"write","object":"files"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"},{"verb":"create","object":"events"},{"verb":"find","object":"images"}]
"search online for the 2026 grants, extract title and deadline, save them to the store, send me the list and schedule a weekly check" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"urls"},{"verb":"extract","object":"entries"},{"verb":"write","object":"entries"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"},{"verb":"create","object":"tasks"}]

Reply ONLY with the JSON, no prose.

